1.what routing is?
In real-world Angular applications, we often need to move from one page to another without reloading the application. Angular provides a feature called Routing, which allows us to navigate between different components smoothly.
In this article, we’ll learn only the two most important concepts:
routerLink
router-outlet
We’ll create a simple application with About, Contact, and Login pages.
2.What We Will Build
Show something like
Press enter or click to view image in full size

• Clicking About opens About component

• Clicking Contact opens Contact component

• Clicking Login opens Login component
3. Create Components
ng generate component home
ng generate component contact
ng generate component login
4. Create Routes
Place below code in app.routes.ts
import { Routes } from '@angular/router';import { AboutComponent } from './about/about.component';
import { ContactComponent } from './contact/contact.component';
import { LoginComponent } from './login/login.component';
export const routes: Routes = [
{
path: 'about',
component: AboutComponent
},
{
path: 'contact',
component: ContactComponent
},
{
path: 'login',
component: LoginComponent
}
];

• Every route has a path

• Every path points to a component

• When the URL changes, Angular loads that component
5. Understanding routerLink
routerLink is used to navigate from one component to another. It changes the URL without reloading the page.
Example:
<a routerLink="/home">Home</a><a routerLink="/contact">Contact</a>
<a routerLink="/login">Login</a>
6. Understanding router-outlet
router-outlet acts as a placeholder where Angular displays the component that matches the current route.
Example
<nav>
<a routerLink="/about">About</a>
<a routerLink="/contact">Contact</a>
<a routerLink="/login">Login</a>
</nav><hr>
<router-outlet></router-outlet>
7.Css Styling(optional)
Place below code in app.component.css
/* Navigation Bar */
nav {
background-color: #2c3e50;
padding: 15px 20px;
display: flex;
gap: 20px;
border-radius: 8px;
}/* Links */
nav a {
color: white;
text-decoration: none;
font-size: 18px;
font-weight: 500;
padding: 8px 15px;
border-radius: 5px;
transition: 0.3s;
}
/* Hover Effect */
nav a:hover {
background-color: #3498db;
}
8. Place below Code In app.component.ts
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterLink, RouterOutlet } from '@angular/router';@Component({
selector: 'app-root',
standalone: true,
imports: [RouterOutlet,RouterLink],
templateUrl: './app.component.html',
styleUrl: './app.component.css'
})
export class AppComponent {
title = 'my-angular-app6';
}
9.How Navigation Works
A small flow diagram
User Clicks Link
│
▼
routerLink Changes URL
│
▼
Angular Router Checks Routes
│
▼
Matching Component Found
│
▼
router-outlet Displays Component
This diagram makes the concept much easier to understand.
